04515nam a22007095i 9780674056961DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979880384  a97806740569617 a10.4159/97806740569612doi  a(DE-B1597)457802  a(OCoLC)785925709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aTRU0030002bisacsh04a306.4/820974711 aWhite, Shane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlaying the Numbers :bGambling in Harlem between the Wars /cGraham White, Stephen Robertson, Stephen Garton, Shane White. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- t1. History -- t2. Beginnings -- t3 Dreams -- t4. Turf Wars -- t5. Numbers’ Lore -- t6. Of Kings and Queens -- t7. The Dutchman Cometh -- t8. Of Banks and Bankers -- t9. All Over Town -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe phrase “Harlem in the 1920s” evokes images of the Harlem Renaissance, or of Marcus Garvey and soapbox orators haranguing crowds about politics and race. Yet the most ubiquitous feature of Harlem life between the world wars was the game of “numbers.” Thousands of wagers, usually of a dime or less, would be placed on a daily number derived from U.S. bank statistics. The rewards of “hitting the number,” a 600-to-1 payoff, tempted the ordinary men and women of the Black Metropolis with the chimera of the good life. Playing the Numbers tells the story of this illegal form of gambling and the central role it played in the lives of African Americans who flooded into Harlem in the wake of World War I. For a dozen years the “numbers game” was one of America’s rare black-owned businesses, turning over tens of millions of dollars every year. The most successful “bankers” were known as Black Kings and Queens, and they lived royally. Yet the very success of “bankers” like Stephanie St. Clair and Casper Holstein attracted Dutch Schultz, Lucky Luciano, and organized crime to the game. By the late 1930s, most of the profits were being siphoned out of Harlem. Playing the Numbers reveals a unique dimension of African American culture that made not only Harlem but New York City itself the vibrant and energizing metropolis it was. An interactive website allows readers to locate actors and events on Harlem’s streets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aTRUE CRIME / Organized Crime.2bisacsh1 aGarton, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRobertson, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067405696140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674056961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674056961.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK